
● This is excellent research. Let me synthesize the findings:

  Current Architecture:

  | Service                       | Responsibility                    |
  |-------------------------------|-----------------------------------|
  | AssignmentSubmissionService   | File storage + Assignment CRUD    |
  | ProcessingPipelineService     | Orchestration + status management |
  | TranscriptProcessorService    | AI formatting of transcripts      |
  | AssignmentRelationshipService | Graph relationship creation       |

  The Key Insight:

  ProcessingPipelineService - orchestrates the processing of ALL assignment types (audio, text, future: PDF, images).

  TranscriptProcessorService is a specialized processor that handles one specific transformation: raw text → formatted document via AI.

  The Architectural Vision:

  AssignmentProcessorService (orchestrator)
      │
      ├── TranscriptProcessorService (text → formatted document)
      ├── [Future] ImageProcessorService (image → extracted data)
      ├── [Future] PDFProcessorService (PDF → text extraction)
      └── [Future] VideoProcessorService (video → transcription + scenes)

  My Recommendation:

  Rather than creating a new AssignmentProcessorService, I suggest:

  1. Rename ProcessingPipelineService → AssignmentProcessorService - This is what it already does: orchestrates assignment processing
  2. Keep TranscriptProcessorService as a specialized processor called by the orchestrator
  3. The naming becomes clear:
    - AssignmentProcessorService - "I process assignments by routing to the right processor"
    - TranscriptProcessorService - "I transform transcripts into formatted documents"

  Benefits:
  - No new service needed (reduces complexity)
  - Clear naming reflects actual responsibilities
  - Room for future processors (Image, PDF, Video) under the orchestrator
